  "prompt": "Derive Maxwell's Equations in Differential form.",
  "response": "Maxwell's equations are fundamental to electromagnetism, governing the behavior of electric and magnetic fields. They can be expressed in both integral and differential forms. Here, we'll derive the differential forms of Maxwell's equations.\n\nTo derive the differential form of Maxwell's equations, we begin with the integral forms:\n\n1. **Gauss's Law for Electricity:**\n   \\[\n   \\Phi_E = \\oint_S \\mathbf{E} \\cdot d\\mathbf{A} = \\frac{Q_{enc}}{\\epsilon_0}\n   \\]\n\n   Applying the Divergence Theorem, we can convert the surface integral over a closed surface \\(S\\) into a volume integral:\n   \\[\n   \\oint_S \\mathbf{E} \\cdot d\\mathbf{A} = \\int_V \\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{E} \\, dV\n   \\]\n   Thus, we have:\n   \\[\n   \\int_V \\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{E} \\, dV = \\frac{Q_{enc}}{\\epsilon_0}\n   \\]\n   Applying the divergence theorem:\n   \\[\n   \\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{E} = \\frac{\\rho}{\\epsilon_0}\n   \\]\n   where \\(\\rho\\) is the charge density.\n\n2. **Gauss's Law for Magnetism:**\n   \\[\n   \\Phi_B = \\oint_S \\mathbf{B} \\cdot d\\mathbf{A} = 0\n   \\]\n   This equation states that there are no magnetic monopoles. By applying the Divergence Theorem:\n   \\[\n   \\oint_S \\mathbf{B} \\cdot d\\mathbf{A} = \\int_V \\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{B} \\, dV = 0\n   \\]\n   Thus, we have:\n   \\[\n   \\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{B} = 0\n   \\]\n\n3. **Faraday's Law of Induction:**\n   \\[\n   \\mathcal{E} = -\\frac{d\\Phi_B}{dt} = -\\frac{d}{dt} \\oint_C \\mathbf{B} \\cdot d\\mathbf{l}\n   \\]\n   Applying Stokes\u2019 Theorem:\n   \\[\n   \\oint_C \\mathbf{E} \\cdot d\\mathbf{l} = \\int_S \\nabla \\times \\mathbf{E} \\cdot d\\mathbf{A}\n   \\]\n   Relating both sides:\n   \\[\n   \\int_S \\nabla \\times \\mathbf{E} \\cdot d\\mathbf{A} = -\\frac{d}{dt} \\int_S \\mathbf{B} \\cdot d\\mathbf{A}\n   \\]\n   Therefore, we conclude:\n   \\[\n   \\nabla \\times \\mathbf{E} = -\\frac{\\partial \\mathbf{B}}{\\partial t}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Amp\u00e8re-Maxwell Law:**\n   The integral form is given by:\n   \\[\n   \\mathcal{I} = \\oint_C \\mathbf{B} \\cdot d\\mathbf{l} = \\mu_0 I_{enc} + \\mu_0 \\epsilon_0 \\frac{d\\Phi_E}{dt}\n   \\]\n   where \\(I_{enc}\\) is the enclosed current. Again, applying Stokes\u2019 theorem yields:\n   \\[\n   \\oint_C \\mathbf{B} \\cdot d\\mathbf{l} = \\int_S (\\nabla \\times \\mathbf{B}) \\cdot d\\mathbf{A}\n   \\]\n   Combining gives:\n   \\[\n   \\int_S (\\nabla \\times \\mathbf{B}) \\cdot d\\mathbf{A} = \\mu_0 \\int_S J \\cdot d\\mathbf{A} + \\mu_0 \\epsilon_0 \\int_S \\frac{\\partial \\mathbf{E}}{\\partial t} \\cdot d\\mathbf{A}\n   \\]\n   Thus we have:\n   \\[\n   \\nabla \\times \\mathbf{B} = \\mu_0 \\mathbf{J} + \\mu_0 \\epsilon_0 \\frac{\\partial \\mathbf{E}}{\\partial t}\n   \\]\n\nCombining all of these results, we have the differential form of Maxwell's equations:\n\n1. Gauss's Law:\n   \\[\n   \\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{E} = \\frac{\\rho}{\\epsilon_0}\n   \\]\n\n2. Gauss's Law for Magnetism:\n   \\[\n   \\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{B} = 0\n   \\]\n\n3. Faraday's Law:\n   \\[\n   \\nabla \\times \\mathbf{E} = -\\frac{\\partial \\mathbf{B}}{\\partial t}\n   \\]\n\n4. Amp\u00e8re-Maxwell Law:\n   \\[\n   \\nabla \\times \\mathbf{B} = \\mu_0 \\mathbf{J} + \\mu_0 \\epsilon_0 \\frac{\\partial \\mathbf{E}}{\\partial t}\n   \\]\n\nThese equations encapsulate the behavior of electric and magnetic fields in space and time.",
